05759nam a22006735i 9780674036833DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221990mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740368337 a10.4159/97806740368332doi  a(DE-B1597)574594  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF540 ǂb F53 1990eb 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a347.306171 aField, Martha A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurrogate Motherhood /cMartha A. Field. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART 1. SURROGACY CONTRACTS -- tChapter One. Are the Contracts Illegal? -- tChapter Two. Exploiting Women and Commercializing Childbearing -- tChapter Three. Do New Reproductive Techniques Threaten the Family? -- tChapter Four. Constitutional Arguments For and Against -- tChapter Five. Making Surrogacy Contracts Unenforceable under Contract Law -- tChapter Six. Integrating Surrogacy with Laws Governing Adoption -- tChapter Seven. Giving the Mother the Right to Renounce the Contract -- tPART II. CUSTODY CONTESTS INDEPENDENT OF THE SURROGACY CONTRACT -- tChapter Eight. Rules Affecting Biological Parents' Claims to Children -- tChapter Nine. Custody Contests to Determine the Better Parent -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: The Current Legal Status of Surrogacy Arrangements -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA practice known since biblical times, surrogate motherhood has only recently leaped to prominence as a way of providing babies for childless couples--and leaped to notoriety through the dramatic case of Baby M. Contract surrogacy is officially little more than ten years old, but by 1986 five hundred babies had been born to mothers who gave them up to sperm donor fathers for a fee, and the practice is growing rapidly. Martha Field examines the myriad legal complexities that today enmesh surrogate motherhood, and also looks beyond existing legal rules to ask what society wants from surrogacy. A man's desire to be a "biological" parent even when his wife is infertile-the father's wife usually adopts the child-has led to this new kind of family, and modern technology could further extend surrogacy's appeal by making gestational surrogates available to couples who provide both egg and sperm. But is surrogacy a form of babyselling? Is the practice a private matter covered by contract law, or does adoption law govern? Is it good or bad social and public policy to leave surrogacy unregulated? Should the law allow, encourage, discourage, or prohibit surrogate motherhood? Ultimately the answers will depend on what the American public wants. In the difficult process of sorting out such vexing questions, Martha Field has written a landmark book. Showing that the problem is rather too much applicable law than too little, she discusses contract law and constitutional law, custody and adoption law, and the rights of biological fathers as well as the laws governing sperm donation. Competing values are involved all along the legal and social spectrum. Field suggests that a federal prohibition would be most effective if banning surrogacy is the aim, but federal prohibition might not be chosen for a variety of reasons: a preference for regulating surrogacy instead of driving it underground; a preference for allowing regulation and variation by state; or a respect for the interests of people who want to enter surrogacy arrangements. Since the law can support a wide variety of positions, Field offers one that seems best to reconcile the competing values at stake. Whether or not paid surrogacy is made illegal, she suggests that a surrogate mother retain the option of abiding by or canceling the contract up to the time she freely gives the child to the adopting couple. And if she cancels the contract, she should be entitled to custody without having to prove in court that she would be a better parent than the father.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674036833zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674036833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674036833/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK